1. The main thesis is that God—understood not as a personal being but as the infinite, all-encompassing creative ground of all existence—permits suffering only because *we* subjectively choose to experience it; suffering and evil are not objective realities imposed from outside, but reflections of our own choices, beliefs, and perspectives within the totality of creation.

2. I find the argument philosophically intriguing but ultimately unconvincing as a full explanation of suffering: while subjective framing *does* shape our experience of pain, it risks minimizing real, systemic harm (e.g., genocide, famine) that victims did not choose—and that many cannot “rechoose” away without structural change. The view conflates *perception* of evil with its *ontological status*, which may offer comfort but not justice.

